[{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0099-0","title":"Zoomorphism","authors":["Bence Nanay"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-19","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"171-186","abstract":"Anthropomorphism is the methodology of attributing human-like mental states to animals. Zoomorphism is the converse of this: it is the attribution of animal-like mental states to humans. Zoomorphism proceeds by first understanding what kind of mental states animals have and then attributing these mental states to humans. Zoomorphism has been widely used as scientific methodology especially in cognitive neuroscience. But it has not been taken seriously as a philosophical explanatory paradigm: as a way of explaining the building blocks of the human mind. The philosophical explanatory paradigm of zoomorphism may not explain all aspects of human behavior (although it may explain surprisingly many), but if we accept the zoomorphic way of thinking about the human mind, we should only posit new, different kinds of mental states if the zoomorphic attribution of animal mental states fails to explain our behavior.","topics":["mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0099-0"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0098-1","title":"How Science and Semantics Settle the Issue of Natural Kind Essentialism","authors":["Christian Nimtz"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-18","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"149-170","abstract":"","topics":["language","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0098-1"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0096-3","title":"Non-eliminative Structuralism, Fregean Abstraction, and Non-rigid Structures","authors":["John Wigglesworth"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-18","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"113-127","abstract":"Linnebo and Pettigrew (Philos Q 64:267–283, 2014) have recently developed a version of non-eliminative mathematical structuralism based on Fregean abstraction principles. They recognize that this version of structuralism is vulnerable to the well-known problem of non-rigid structures. This paper offers a solution to the problem for this version of structuralism. The solution involves expanding the languages used to describe mathematical structures. We then argue that this solution is philosophically acceptable to those who endorse mathematical structuralism based on Fregean abstraction principles.","topics":["history","logic","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0096-3"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0082-9","title":"Confirmation and Meaning Holism Revisited","authors":["Timothy Fuller"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-17","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1379-1397","abstract":"","topics":["language","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0082-9"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0095-4","title":"Mechanisms and Relations","authors":["Michele Paolini Paoletti"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-14","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"95-111","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0095-4"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0097-2","title":"Twofileness. A Functionalist Approach to Fictional Characters and Mental Files","authors":["Enrico Terrone"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-13","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"129-147","abstract":"","topics":["aesthetics","mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0097-2"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0079-4","title":"Rawls’s Self-Defeat: A Formal Analysis","authors":["Hun Chung"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-07","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1169-1197","abstract":"One of John Rawls’s major aims, when he wrote A Theory of Justice , was to present a superior alternative to utilitarianism. Rawls’s worry was that utilitarianism may fail to protect the fundamental rights and liberties of persons in its attempt to maximize total social welfare. Rawls’s main argument against utilitarianism was that, for such reasons, the representative parties in the original position will not choose utilitarianism, but will rather choose his justice as fairness, which he believed would securely protect the worth of everybody’s basic rights and liberties. In this paper, I will argue that, under close formal examination, Rawls’s argument against utilitarianism is self-defeating. That is, I will argue that Rawls’s own reasons, assumptions, and the many theoretical devices he employs demonstrably imply that the representative parties in the original position will choose utilitarianism instead of justice as fairness.","topics":["ethics","philsci","political"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0079-4"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0086-5","title":"Counterfactuals and Non-exceptionalism About Modal Knowledge","authors":["Daniel Dohrn"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-04","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1461-1483","abstract":"","topics":["epistemology","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0086-5"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0084-7","title":"Indirectly Free Actions, Libertarianism, and Resultant Moral Luck","authors":["Robert J. Hartman"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-03","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1417-1436","abstract":"Martin Luther affirms his theological position by saying “Here I stand. I can do no other.” Supposing that Luther’s claim is true, he lacks alternative possibilities at the moment of choice. Even so, many libertarians have the intuition that he is morally responsible for his action. One way to make sense of this intuition is to assert that Luther’s action is indirectly free, because his action inherits its freedom and moral responsibility from earlier actions when he had alternative possibilities and those earlier directly free actions formed him into the kind of person who must refrain from recanting. Surprisingly, libertarians have not developed a full account of indirectly free actions. I provide a more developed account. First, I explain the metaphysical nature of indirectly free actions such as Luther’s. Second, I examine the kind of metaphysical and epistemic connections that must occur between past directly free actions and the indirectly free action. Third, I argue that an attractive way to understand the kind of derivative moral responsibility at issue involves affirming the existence of resultant moral luck.","topics":["action","blame-resp","epistemology","ethics","metaphil","metaphysics","philsci","political"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0084-7"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0091-8","title":"Analytic Metaphysics Versus Naturalized Metaphysics: The Relevance of Applied Ontology","authors":["Baptiste Le Bihan","Adrien Barton"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-01","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"21-37","abstract":"","topics":["metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0091-8"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0087-4","title":"Approaching Truth in Conceptual Spaces","authors":["Gustavo Cevolani"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-12-01","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1485-1500","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0087-4"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0092-7","title":"Moral Responsibility Without Personal Identity?","authors":["Sebastian Köhler"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-30","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"39-58","abstract":"","topics":["blame-resp","ethics","metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0092-7"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0083-8","title":"Grounding Pluralism: Why and How","authors":["Kevin Richardson"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-30","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1399-1415","abstract":"","topics":["metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0083-8"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0090-9","title":"Prediction Error Minimization as a Framework for Social Cognition Research","authors":["Leon de Bruin","John Michael"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-30","volume":"86","issue":"1","pages":"1-20","abstract":"The main aim of this article is to give an assessment of prediction error minimization (PEM) as a unifying theoretical framework for the study of social cognition. We show how this framework can be used to synthesize and systematically relate existing data from social cognition research, and explain how it introduces new constraints for further research. We discuss PEM in relation to other theoretical frameworks of social cognition, and identify the main challenges that this approach to social cognition will need to address.","topics":["mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0090-9"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0085-6","title":"What is the Point of Reduction in Science?","authors":["Karen Crowther"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-30","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1437-1460","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0085-6"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0088-3","title":"Metaphysical and Conceptual Grounding","authors":["Robert Smithson"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-30","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1501-1525","abstract":"","topics":["metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0088-3"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0070-0","title":"Admissibility Troubles for Bayesian Direct Inference Principles","authors":["Christian Wallmann","James Hawthorne"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-24","volume":"85","issue":"4","pages":"957-993","abstract":"","topics":["logic","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0070-0"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0037-1","title":"The Termination Risks of Simulation Science","authors":["Preston Greene"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-23","volume":"85","issue":"2","pages":"489-509","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0037-1"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0081-x","title":"Perceptual Knowledge, Discrimination, and Closure","authors":["Santiago Echeverri"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-19","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1361-1378","abstract":"","topics":["epistemology","mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0081-x"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0056-y","title":"Non-contractability and Revenge","authors":["Julien Murzi","Lorenzo Rossi"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-15","volume":"85","issue":"4","pages":"905-917","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0056-y"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0078-5","title":"Analyzing Theories in the Frame Model","authors":["Stephan Kornmesser","Gerhard Schurz"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-08","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1313-1346","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0078-5"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0073-x","title":"Quine’s Intuition: Why Quine’s Early Nominalism is Naturalistic","authors":["James Andrew Smith"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-08","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1199-1218","abstract":"","topics":["metaphil","metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0073-x"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0074-9","title":"Instrumental Rationality Without Separability","authors":["Johanna Thoma"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-01","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1219-1240","abstract":"This paper argues that instrumental rationality is more permissive than expected utility theory. The most compelling instrumentalist argument in favour of separability, its core requirement, is that agents with non-separable preferences end up badly off by their own lights in some dynamic choice problems. I argue that once we focus on the question of whether agents’ attitudes to uncertain prospects help define their ends in their own right, or instead only assign instrumental value in virtue of the outcomes they may lead to, we see that the argument must fail. Either attitudes to prospects assign non-instrumental value in their own right, in which case we cannot establish the irrationality of the dynamic choice behaviour of agents with non-separable preferences. Or they don’t, in which case agents with non-separable preferences can avoid the problematic choice behaviour without adopting separable preferences.","topics":["epistemology","mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0074-9"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0076-7","title":"The Self-Hollowing Problem of the Radical Sceptical Paradox","authors":["Changsheng Lai"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-01","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1269-1288","abstract":"The purpose of this paper is to provide a new solution to the radical sceptical paradox. A sceptical paradox purports to indicate the inconsistency within our fundamental epistemological commitments that are all seemingly plausible. Typically, sceptics employ an intuitively appealing epistemic principle (e.g., the closure principle, the underdetermination principle) to derive the sceptical conclusion. This paper will reveal a dilemma intrinsic to the sceptical paradox, which I refer to as the self - hollowing problem of radical scepticism. That is, on the one hand, if the sceptical conclusion turns out to be true, then the epistemic principle employed by sceptics would lose its foundation of plausibility; on the other hand, if the sceptical conclusion does not follow, then the sceptical problem would not arise. In either case, the so-called sceptical paradox cannot be a genuine paradox. This new solution has three theoretical merits: it is undercutting, less theory-laden, and widely applicable.","topics":["epistemology","logic","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0076-7"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0071-z","title":"A Minimality Constraint on Grounding","authors":["Jonas Werner"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-01","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1153-1168","abstract":"","topics":["metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0071-z"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0075-8","title":"The Irreducibility of Emotional Phenomenology","authors":["Jonathan Mitchell"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-11-01","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1241-1268","abstract":"Emotion theory includes attempts to reduce or assimilate emotions to states such as bodily feelings, beliefs-desire combinations, and evaluative judgements. Resistance to such approaches is motivated by the claim that emotions possess a sui generis phenomenology. Uriah Kriegel defends a new form of emotion reductivism which avoids positing irreducible emotional phenomenology by specifying emotions’ phenomenal character in terms of a combination of other phenomenologies. This article argues Kriegel’s approach, and similar proposals, are unsuccessful, since typical emotional experiences are constituted by sui generis feelings towards value.","topics":["mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0075-8"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0077-6","title":"In Defense of Donnellan on Proper Names","authors":["Antonio Capuano"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-10-31","volume":"85","issue":"6","pages":"1289-1312","abstract":"","topics":["language","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0077-6"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0060-2","title":"The Neural Dynamics of Seeing-In","authors":["Gabriele Ferretti"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-10-03","volume":"84","issue":"6","pages":"1285-1324","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0060-2"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0066-9","title":"Faultless Disagreement, Realism and Moral Objectivity","authors":["Manfred Harth"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-28","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1085-1108","abstract":"","topics":["epistemology","ethics","metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0066-9"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0069-6","title":"Consciousness, Conceivability, and Intrinsic Reduction","authors":["Jonathon VandenHombergh"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-24","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1129-1151","abstract":"","topics":["mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0069-6"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0065-x","title":"Realists Waiting for Godot? The Verisimilitudinarian and the Cumulative Approach to Scientific Progress","authors":["Andrea Roselli"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-24","volume":"85","issue":"5","pages":"1071-1084","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0065-x"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0068-7","title":"Against Grue Mysteries","authors":["Alexandra Zinke"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-22","volume":"85","issue":"4","pages":"1023-1033","abstract":"","topics":["philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0068-7"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0062-0","title":"How to Be a Pluralist in Substance Ontology","authors":["Travis Dumsday"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-20","volume":"85","issue":"4","pages":"995-1022","abstract":"","topics":["metaphysics","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0062-0"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0059-8","title":"Interventionism and Mental Surgery","authors":["Alex Kaiserman"],"journal":"erkenntnis","published":"2018-09-17","volume":"85","issue":"4","pages":"919-935","abstract":"","topics":["mind","philsci"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10670-018-0059-8"},{"doi":"10.1007/s10670-018-0063-z","title":"The Rea